# Current version
# v2.9
# 11/13/2025
# 
# Format: tdar [-b, -s, or -p] <file_name> [field_name] [date]
# The -b (by-line), -s (skip), and -p (print-out) flags, along with field_name and date, are optional.
# file_name is required.
# file_name must be entered in its entirety.
# file_name MUST be the first argument or immediately follow any flags used.
# Date MUST be in the mmddyyyy format.
#
# Users can use periods, slashes, or dashes to separate the month, day, and year, as long as it maintains the mmddyyyy structure.
# Valid date examples:
# 11.13.2025
# 11-13-2025
# 11/13/2025
#
# --------------------------------------------
# FLAG OPTIONS
# --------------------------------------------
#
# Use the "-b" flag to list each date entry one by one.
# The script will pause after each entry until Enter is pressed.
# Example:
#	tdar -b <file_name> [field_name] [date]
#
# Use the "-s" flag to skip the detailed per-date listing and only display the complete totals of the file.
# Example:
#	tdar -s <file_name> [field_name] [date]
#
# Use the "-p" flag to print the results of the command into a text file.
# Example:
#	tdar -p <file_name> [field_name] [date]
#
# When using the "-p" flag, the script will prompt for a store number.
# The created file will be named:
#	"Results for <store_number> [field_name] [date].txt"
#
# The -s and -p flags can be used together.
# The -b flag can only be used alone.
#
# --------------------------------------------
# EXAMPLES
# --------------------------------------------
#
#	tdar testDAR.json
#	tdar testDAR.json TotalSales 10-20-2025
#	tdar testDAR.json 10-20-2025
#	tdar -b testDAR.json
#	tdar -s testDAR.json TotalSales
#	tdar -p testDAR.json TotalSales 10-20-2025
